SIMPLE: hobble
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hobble
<hw>Hob"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Hobbled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hobbling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hobelen</ets>, <ets>hoblen</ets>, freq. of <ets>hoppen</ets> to
hop; akin to D. <ets>hobbelen</ets>, <ets>hoblen</ets>,
<ets>hoppeln</ets>. See <er>Hop</er> to jump, and cf. <er>Hopple</er>
]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To walk lame, bearing chiefly on one leg; to
walk with a hitch or hop, or with crutches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The friar was <qex>hobbling</qex> the same way too.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move roughly or irregularly; -- said of style in
writing.</def> <rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>hobbling</qex> versification, the mean diction.</q>
<rj><qau>Jeffreys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hobble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hobble
<hw>Hob"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fetter by tying
the legs; to hopple; to clog.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ They <xex>hobbled</xex>
their horses.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dickens</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perplex; to embarrass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hobble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hobble
<hw>Hob"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An unequal gait; a
limp; a halt; <as>as, he has a <ex>hobble</ex> in his gait</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <er>Hopple</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Difficulty; perplexity; embarrassment.</def>
<rj><au>Waterton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hobblebush</ent>⟦br⟧
